PROJECTS/PROGRAMS

IREX 10: Identification Track


Results

This page presents performance results for the Identification track of the Iris Exchange (IREX) 10 evaluation of iris recognition technology. Most flagship deployments of iris recognition operate in identification mode, providing services ranging from prison management, border security, expedited processing, and distribution of resources. Administered at the Image Group’s Biometrics Research Lab (BRL), developers submit their matching software for testing over sequestered iris data. As an ongoing evaluation, developers may submit at any time. The results of this ongoing evaluation are presented below.

IREX 10 Homepage

Leaderboard

Test Parameters
Accuracy Metric: FNIR (i.e., ‘miss rate’) at an FPIR of 0.01
Dataset: Operational Dataset 4
Samples used: Both eyes
Enrolled Population: 500K people
Enrollment Method: One enrollment session per person

Core accuracy is assessed using the 4th pull from the Operational Dataset. This iris image dataset is sequestered, meaning the participants are not granted access to the images, thereby preventing overtraining or fine-tuning to the images contained within the dataset. OPS 4 images are sometimes characterized as “field collected”, having been acquired in a variety of indoor and outdoor environments. In contrast, datastets collected in more controlled university settings tend to suffer less from quality related problems (e.g. motion and focus blur).

Speed

Times are measured as the the elapsed real time (i.e., “wall clock”) as opposed to CPU time. Timing estimates were computed on unloaded machines with only a single process dedicated to biometric operations. The test machines are Dell PowerEdge M910 blades with Dual Intel Xeon X7560 2.3 GHz CPUs (eight cores per processor).
